<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_analysis" title=
=3D"Mathematical analysis">mathematical analysis</a>, the <b>Taylor series<=
/b> or <b>Taylor expansion</b> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Function_(mathematics)" title=3D"Function (mathematics)">function</a> is =
an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Series_(mathematics)" title=3D"=
Series (mathematics)">infinite sum</a> of terms that are expressed in terms=
 of the function's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derivative" tit=
le=3D"Derivative">derivatives</a> at a single point. For most common functi=
ons, the function and the sum of its Taylor series are equal near this poin=
t. Taylor series are named after <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B=
rook_Taylor" title=3D"Brook Taylor">Brook Taylor</a>, who introduced them i=
n 1715. A Taylor series is also called a <b>Maclaurin series</b> when 0 is =
the point where the derivatives are considered, after <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colin_Maclaurin" title=3D"Colin Maclaurin">Colin Maclau=
rin</a>, who made extensive use of this special case of Taylor series in th=
e 18th century.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partial_sum" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Partial sum">partial sum</a> formed by the first <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> + 1</span> terms of a Taylor series is a <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial" title=3D"Polynomial">polynom=
ial</a> of degree <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"=
>n</span> that is called the <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-sty=
le:italic;">n</span>th <b>Taylor polynomial</b> of the function. Taylor pol=
ynomials are approximations of a function, which become generally more accu=
rate as <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> =
increases. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taylor%27s_theorem" tit=
le=3D"Taylor's theorem">Taylor's theorem</a> gives quantitative estimates o=
n the error introduced by the use of such approximations. If the Taylor ser=
ies of a function is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convergence_(=
mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Convergence (mathematics)">con=
vergent</a>, its sum is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limit_=
of_a_sequence" title=3D"Limit of a sequence">limit</a> of the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinite_sequence" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Infinite sequence">infinite sequence</a> of the Taylor polynomials. A f=
unction may differ from the sum of its Taylor series, even if its Taylor se=
ries is convergent. A function is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Analytic_function" title=3D"Analytic function">analytic</a> at a point <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> if it is equ=
al to the sum of its Taylor series in some <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Open_interval" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Open interval">open =
interval</a> (or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disk_(mathematics=
)" title=3D"Disk (mathematics)">open disk</a> in the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_plane" title=3D"Complex plane">complex plane</a>=
) containing <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</s=
pan>. This implies that the function is analytic at every point of the inte=
rval (or disk).
</p>
