<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTaylor_series&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Greek_philosopher" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ancient Greek philosopher">ancient Greek phi=
losopher</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zeno_of_Elea" title=
=3D"Zeno of Elea">Zeno of Elea</a> considered the problem of summing an inf=
inite series to achieve a finite result, but rejected it as an impossibilit=
y;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELindberg200733_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taylor_series#cite_note-FOOTNOTELindber=
g200733-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> the result was <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Zeno%27s_paradox" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Zeno's paradox">Zeno's =
paradox</a>. Later, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aristotle" tit=
le=3D"Aristotle">Aristotle</a> proposed a philosophical resolution of the p=
aradox, but the mathematical content was apparently unresolved until taken =
up by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archimedes" title=3D"Archime=
des">Archimedes</a>, as it had been prior to Aristotle by the Presocratic A=
tomist <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Democritus" title=3D"Democr=
itus">Democritus</a>. It was through Archimedes's <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Method_of_exhaustion" title=3D"Method of exhaustion">method=
 of exhaustion</a> that an infinite number of progressive subdivisions coul=
d be performed to achieve a finite result.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKline=
1990[httpsarchiveorgdetailsmathematicalthou00klinpagen437_35]=E2=80=9337_4-=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taylor_seri=
es#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKline1990[httpsarchiveorgdetailsmathematicalthou00klin=
pagen437_35]%E2%80%9337-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Liu_Hui" title=3D"Liu Hui">Liu Hui</a> independently employed a similar=
 method a few centuries later.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBoyerMerzbach1991=
[httpsarchiveorgdetailshistoryofmathema00boyepage202_202=E2=80=93203]_5-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taylor_series#=
cite_note-FOOTNOTEBoyerMerzbach1991[httpsarchiveorgdetailshistoryofmathema0=
0boyepage202_202%E2%80%93203]-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the 14th century, the earliest examples of specific Taylor series=
 (but not the general method) were given by the Indian mathematician <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Madhava_of_Sangamagrama" title=3D"Madhav=
a of Sangamagrama">Madhava of Sangamagrama</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTE=
Dani2012_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Taylor_series#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDani2012-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
