and so the power series expansion agrees with the Taylor series. Thus, a fu=
nction is analytic in an open disk centered at <span class=3D"texhtml mvar"=
 style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> if and only if its Taylor series con=
verges to the value of the function at each point of the disk.
</p><p>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>=E2=80=89(<i>x</i>)</span> is equ=
al to the sum of its Taylor series for all <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" sty=
le=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> in the complex plane, it is called <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entire_function" title=3D"Entire functi=
on">entire</a>. The polynomials, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
xponential_function" title=3D"Exponential function">exponential function</a=
> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>e</i><sup><i>x</i></sup></span>, and the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trigonometric_function" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Trigonometric function">trigonometric functions</a> of sine=
 and cosine, are examples of entire functions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEM=
arkushevich1966[httpbooksgooglecombooksid-rvSBQAAQBAJpgPA6_6]_14-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taylor_series#cite_=
note-FOOTNOTEMarkushevich1966[httpbooksgooglecombooksid-rvSBQAAQBAJpgPA6_6]=
-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> Examples of functions that are not entire include the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_root" title=3D"Square root">squ=
are root</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm" title=
=3D"Logarithm">logarithm</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Trigonometric_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Trigonometric functi=
on">trigonometric function</a> tangent, and its inverse, <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arctan" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Arctan">arcta=
n</a>. For these functions, the Taylor series do not <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Convergent_series" title=3D"Convergent series">converge<=
/a> if <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> i=
s far from <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</spa=
n>. That is, the Taylor series <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Div=
ergent_series" title=3D"Divergent series">diverges</a> at <span class=3D"te=
xhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> if the distance between <=
span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> and <span=
 class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> is larger tha=
n the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radius_of_convergence" title=
=3D"Radius of convergence">radius of convergence</a>. The Taylor series can=
 be used to calculate the value of an entire function at every point, provi=
ded the value of the function and all its derivatives are known at a single=
 point.
</p><p>Uses of the Taylor series for analytic functions include:
</p>
<ul><li>The partial sums (the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tayl=
or_polynomial" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Taylor polynomial">Taylor pol=
ynomials</a>) of the series can be used as approximations of the function. =
These approximations are good if sufficiently many terms are included.</li>
<li>Differentiation and integration of power series can be performed term b=
y term and are hence particularly easy.</li>
<li>An <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_function" title=3D=
"Analytic function">analytic function</a> is uniquely extended to a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Holomorphic_function" title=3D"Holomorphi=
c function">holomorphic function</a> on an open disk in the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number" title=3D"Complex number">complex =
plane</a>. This makes the machinery of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Complex_analysis" title=3D"Complex analysis">complex analysis</a> avai=
lable.</li>
<li>The (truncated) series can be used to compute function values numerical=
ly, often by recasting the polynomial into the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Chebyshev_form" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Chebyshev form"=
>Chebyshev form</a> and evaluating it with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Clenshaw_algorithm" title=3D"Clenshaw algorithm">Clenshaw algo=
rithm</a>.</li>
<li>Algebraic operations can be done readily on the power series representa=
tion; for instance, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler%27s_form=
ula" title=3D"Euler's formula">Euler's formula</a> follows from Taylor seri=
es expansions for trigonometric and exponential functions. This result is o=
f fundamental importance in such fields as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Harmonic_analysis" title=3D"Harmonic analysis">harmonic analysis</=
a>.</li>
<li>Approximations using the first few terms of a Taylor series can make ot=
herwise unsolvable problems possible for a restricted domain; this approach=
 is often used in physics.</li></ul>
