able</a> at <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =3D 0</span>, and has all deri=
vatives zero there. Consequently, the Taylor series of <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><i>f</i>=E2=80=89(<i>x</i>)</span> about <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</=
i> =3D 0</span> is identically zero. However, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f<=
/i>=E2=80=89(<i>x</i>)</span> is not the zero function, so it does not equa=
l its Taylor series around the origin.  Thus, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f<=
/i>=E2=80=89(<i>x</i>)</span> is an example of a <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Non-analytic_smooth_function" title=3D"Non-analytic smooth f=
unction">non-analytic smooth function</a>. This example shows that there ar=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinitely_differentiable_functi=
on" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Infinitely differentiable function">infi=
nitely differentiable functions</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>=E2=80=
=89(<i>x</i>)</span> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_analy=
sis" title=3D"Real analysis">real analysis</a>, whose Taylor series are <i>=
not</i> equal to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>=E2=80=89(<i>x</i>)</span>=
 even if they converge.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGrossman1984[httpbooksgo=
oglecombooksideafiBQAAQBAJpgPA750_750]_16-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taylor_series#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGrossman1984=
[httpbooksgooglecombooksideafiBQAAQBAJpgPA750_750]-16"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> By contr=
ast, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Holomorphic_function" tit=
le=3D"Holomorphic function">holomorphic functions</a> studied in <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_analysis" title=3D"Complex analysis"=
>complex analysis</a> always possess a convergent Taylor series, and even t=
he Taylor series of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meromorphic_=
function" title=3D"Meromorphic function">meromorphic function</a>, which mi=
ght have singularities, never converges to a value different from the funct=
ion itself. The complex function <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>e</i><sup>=E2=
=88=921/<i>z</i><sup>2</sup></sup></span>, however, does not approach 0 whe=
n <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">z</span> approa=
ches 0 along the imaginary axis, so it is not <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Continuous_function" title=3D"Continuous function">continuous</=
a> in the complex plane and its Taylor series is undefined at 0.
</p><p>Every sequence of real or complex numbers can appear more generally =
as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coefficient" title=3D"Coefficie=
nt">coefficients</a> in the Taylor series of an infinitely differentiable f=
unction defined on the real line, a consequence of <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Borel%27s_lemma" title=3D"Borel's lemma">Borel's lemma</a>=
.  As a result, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radius_of_conv=
ergence" title=3D"Radius of convergence">radius of convergence</a> of a Tay=
lor series can be zero. There are even infinitely differentiable functions =
defined on the real line whose Taylor series have a radius of convergence 0=
 everywhere.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTERudin1980418See_Exercise_13_17-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taylor_series#c=
ite_note-FOOTNOTERudin1980418See_Exercise_13-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A function cannot be written as a Taylor series centred at a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Singularity_(mathematics)" title=3D"Singu=
larity (mathematics)">singularity</a>. In these cases, one can often still =
achieve a series expansion if one also allows negative powers of the variab=
le <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span>. For =
example, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>f</i>=E2=80=89(<i>x</i>) =3D <i>e</i><s=
up>=E2=88=921/<i>x</i><sup>2</sup></sup></span> can be written as a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laurent_series" title=3D"Laurent series">=
Laurent series</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Generalization">Generalizat=
ion</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTaylor_s=
eries&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Generalizat=
ion"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></=
span></div>
<p>The generalization of the Taylor series does converge to the value of th=
e function itself for any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bounded_=
function" title=3D"Bounded function">bounded</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Continuous_function" title=3D"Continuous function">continuou=
s function</a> on <span class=3D"texhtml">(0,=E2=88=9E)</span>, and this ca=
n be done by using the calculus of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Finite_differences" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Finite differences">fin=
ite differences</a>. Specifically, the following theorem, due to <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Einar_Hille" title=3D"Einar Hille">Einar Hil=
le</a>, that for any <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>t</i> &gt; 0</span>,<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Taylor_series#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle \lim _{h\to 0^{+}}\sum _{n=3D0}^{\infty }{\frac {t^{n}}{n!}}{\f=
rac {\Delta _{h}^{n}f(a)}{h^{n}}}=3Df(a+t).}">
