<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Calculation_of_Taylor_serie=
s">Calculation of Taylor series</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DTaylor_series&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=
=3D"Edit section: Calculation of Taylor series"><span>edit</span></a><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Several methods exist for the calculation of the Taylor series of a larg=
e number of functions. One can attempt to use the definition of the Taylor =
series, though this often requires generalizing the form of the coefficient=
s according to a readily apparent pattern.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVarbe=
rgPurcellRigdon2007489_28-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Taylor_series#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVarbergPurcellRigdon2007489-=
28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> Alternatively, one can use manipulations such as substituti=
on, multiplication or division, addition or subtraction of standard Taylor =
series to construct the Taylor series of a function, by virtue of the Taylo=
r series being a power series. In some cases, one can also derive the Taylo=
r series by repeatedly applying <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In=
tegration_by_parts" title=3D"Integration by parts">integration by parts</a>=
. Particularly convenient is the use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Computer_algebra_system" title=3D"Computer algebra system">computer a=
lgebra systems</a> to calculate Taylor series.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"First_example">First exampl=
e</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DTaylor_ser=
ies&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: First exampl=
e"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<p>In order to compute the 7th-degree Maclaurin polynomial for the function
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle f(x)=3D\ln(\cos x),\quad x\in {\bigl (}{-{\tfrac {\pi }{2}}},{\=
tfrac {\pi }{2}}{\bigr )},}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>f</mi>
