<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Taylor_series_as_definition=
s">Taylor series as definitions</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DTaylor_series&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=
=3D"Edit section: Taylor series as definitions"><span>edit</span></a><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Classically, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_function=
" title=3D"Algebraic function">algebraic functions</a> are defined by an al=
gebraic equation, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transcendent=
al_function" title=3D"Transcendental function">transcendental functions</a>=
 (including those discussed above) are defined by some property that holds =
for them, such as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_e=
quation" title=3D"Differential equation">differential equation</a>. For exa=
mple, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_function" ti=
tle=3D"Exponential function">exponential function</a> is the function which=
 is equal to its own derivative everywhere, and assumes the value 1 at the =
origin. However, one may equally well define an <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Analytic_function" title=3D"Analytic function">analytic funct=
ion</a> by its Taylor series.
</p><p>Taylor series are used to define functions and "<a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operator_(mathematics)" title=3D"Operator (mathematics=
)">operators</a>" in diverse areas of mathematics. In particular, this is t=
rue in areas where the classical definitions of functions break down. For e=
xample, using Taylor series, one may extend analytic functions to sets of m=
atrices and operators, such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Matrix_exponential" title=3D"Matrix exponential">matrix exponential</a> or=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_logarithm" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Matrix logarithm">matrix logarithm</a>.
</p><p>In other areas, such as formal analysis, it is more convenient to wo=
rk directly with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_series"=
 title=3D"Power series">power series</a> themselves. Thus one may define a =
solution of a differential equation <i>as</i> a power series which, one hop=
es to prove, is the Taylor series of the desired solution.
</p>
